00:02:51.490 --> 00:02:54.640
I grew up in Southern
California and recently moved

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:56.900
to the DC area.

00:02:56.900 --> 00:03:00.430
And so I decided that
I needed to get out,

00:03:00.430 --> 00:03:03.790
see what's going on in
Virginia, since that

00:03:03.790 --> 00:03:05.290
was going to be my new home.

00:03:05.290 --> 00:03:07.460
And that started with a hike--

00:03:07.460 --> 00:03:08.770
so getting out enjoying nature.

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:10.850
I came from Southern California.

00:03:10.850 --> 00:03:12.850
These whole things called
seasons, which kind of

00:03:12.850 --> 00:03:14.225
dictate what you
can do and where

00:03:14.225 --> 00:03:16.000
you can do it were new to me.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:17.260
So summertime was around.

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:19.520
This is July 2015.

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:22.030
I would go for a hike,
take some photos,

00:03:22.030 --> 00:03:25.360
come back home, load them up
in my computer, and open a map.

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:31.090
And that's where I
see that I just was.

00:03:31.090 --> 00:03:34.030
There's a stream there
called Negro Run.

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:36.550
And when I first saw it
come up on Google Maps,

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:39.280
I thought that has to be a typo.

00:03:39.280 --> 00:03:40.780
There's no way that
there's actually

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:43.850
a place called Negro Run.

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:45.700
And it kind of sat
with me a little bit.

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:47.860
And as I was
thinking about it, I

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:51.590
was considering, OK, well,
it's obviously not a typo.

00:03:51.590 --> 00:03:54.162
There's some history that
I need to learn about.

00:03:54.162 --> 00:03:55.870
So over the course of
the following weeks

00:03:55.870 --> 00:03:58.720
and a couple of months,
I began to learn

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:00.850
more about the history
of Shenandoah National

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:05.290
Park and its own struggles with
segregation and desegregation

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:07.120
in the '30s and '40s.

00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:08.970
And I just had this
feeling in my stomach

00:04:08.970 --> 00:04:10.720
that it just-- it
didn't sit well with me,

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:13.720
that that was a name
that was still there.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:15.640
And so I thought, I
need to change that.

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:18.370
That's something that I
don't want to be around

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:20.560
when I go out to enjoy nature.

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:26.210
So I started that process of
basically just shooting off

00:04:26.210 --> 00:04:27.899
emails as far as I
could to whoever I

00:04:27.899 --> 00:04:30.065
could think of that might
actually have some powers.

00:04:30.065 --> 00:04:34.100
So I sent emails off to the
park superintendent, the region

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:38.360
director, the director of
the national park system,

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:40.850
the Secretary of the Department
of Interior, just anyone

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:42.558
that I could think of
that might actually

00:04:42.558 --> 00:04:45.665
have some power to help
make this change come about.

00:04:45.665 --> 00:04:47.810
BRANDI: Wow.

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:49.880
So when you were
doing this research,

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.850
you used Google Maps to identify
the place that you were at.

00:04:52.850 --> 00:04:55.250
And then you named a couple
of different agencies.

00:04:55.250 --> 00:04:58.204
In your process of
discovery this place name,

00:04:58.204 --> 00:05:00.120
what did you learn about
other offensive place

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:02.020
names in the US?

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:04.820
MAURICE TURNER: Well, I learned
that they're everywhere.

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:07.250
They are literally
racist place names

00:05:07.250 --> 00:05:10.340
all over the country
in every state

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:12.210
that we have in our country.

00:05:12.210 --> 00:05:15.920
And so it was just
really shocking to me

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:18.470
that we could have names
like this that would reflect

00:05:18.470 --> 00:05:21.720
a time in history
that wasn't inclusive,

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:23.780
that didn't respect the
diversity that we now

00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:25.880
have in our country.

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:28.580
And thankfully, the
government agency

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:31.100
that's in charge of
recognizing these names

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:32.120
is very well documented.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:34.100
They've been around since 1890.

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:37.880
And so as you can
see, there are cards--

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:39.080
name cards.

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:40.580
And one of the
things that I learned

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:45.080
was that Negro Run was
actually a compromised name.

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:49.040
That was a name that was
applied in the early '60s.

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:53.900
It used to be called Nigger
Run, which is something that I

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:55.060
had to come to terms with.

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:57.500
It's not a word that I
like to use or a word

00:05:57.500 --> 00:05:58.910
that I like to hear.

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:01.860
But I recognize that
our words have power.

00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:06.170
And there is a certain
power in using that word,

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:09.260
either toward people
or around people,

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:11.180
because it's meant to hurt.

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:14.450
It's meant to inflict
a level of pain

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:16.160
upon people that
are being referred

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.410
to in a derogatory sense.

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:21.500
And that helped push me toward
going through the effort

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:23.450
and following up over
the months, which

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:27.500
ended up being over a year,
to get the name changed.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.660
Interesting little
note of history--

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:31.910
1933, as we saw
on that name card,

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:34.760
the name was actually
changed to Nigger Run.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.670
I believe that there is a
correlation between the timing

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:44.240
of that change being 1933,
because in 1932, the Shenandoah

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:47.650
National Park was actually
supposed to have a concession

00:06:47.650 --> 00:06:50.960
facilities built in an area of
the park that was desegregated

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:53.860
and meant to serve
only colored people,

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:55.760
as they referred to at the time.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:58.120
So in my mind, the only
reason that the name

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:01.000
could have been changed from
its original name, Tims River,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.220
to something that is
so blatantly offensive

00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:06.190
is that there were a
dedicated group of people

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:09.426
who lived nearby that felt so
strongly that the named needed

00:07:09.426 --> 00:07:11.050
to change that they
actually petitioned

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:14.350
the federal government and
proposed to have this change.

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:17.230
And then that committee, the
Domestic Names Committee,

00:07:17.230 --> 00:07:21.570
actually agreed to
change the name.

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:23.910
BRANDI: What was the process
like to actually find

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:24.930
this documentation?

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:27.822
Was it relatively easy to
uncover these documents?

00:07:27.822 --> 00:07:29.530
MAURICE TURNER: The
information is there,

00:07:29.530 --> 00:07:30.890
but it's not easy to get to.

00:07:30.890 --> 00:07:33.000
So obviously, you
need to know that it's

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.150
the Department of the
Interior that is then

00:07:36.150 --> 00:07:38.340
over the US
Geological Survey that

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:41.730
is in over the Board of
Geographic Names, which

00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:43.950
is the home of the
Domestic Names Committee.

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:46.440
So you have to go through
several layers of bureaucracy

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.050
to actually find out who is
responsible for the names

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:51.570
and where that
information is kept.

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:52.680
So it took some digging.

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:53.910
It took some research.

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:57.900
Thankfully, we're living in a
time where a lot of information

00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:00.750
is available online, if we're
willing to search for it.

00:08:00.750 --> 00:08:02.040
So I was able to find it.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:04.500
And they were very diligent
in their recordkeeping.

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:06.810
And so that's how I was
able to find that name card

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:10.770
and find those board minutes,
where they actually captured

00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:13.680
some of their conversations
they had at board meetings

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:15.689
to make some of
these name changes.

00:08:15.689 --> 00:08:18.230
BRANDI: Can you tell us a little
bit about this documentation

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:19.512
right here?

00:08:19.512 --> 00:08:23.220
MAURICE TURNER: Certainly,
in the early '60s,

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:26.760
then Secretary of the Department
of Interior Udall sent out

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:31.590
a memo saying that, as part of
the rise of the Civil Rights

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:35.490
Movement at the time, it
became clear that there were

00:08:35.490 --> 00:08:38.250
certain names and
certain words that

00:08:38.250 --> 00:08:41.400
were universally derogatory.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:46.490
And so he directed
the names committee

00:08:46.490 --> 00:08:49.460
to make a system wide
change, so to change

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:53.240
every instance of nigger
to negro, which in his mind

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:56.620
was a more appropriate
name to use,

00:08:56.620 --> 00:08:58.820
which here we are
these years later,

00:08:58.820 --> 00:09:01.859
that is still as offensive
as I'm sure it was then.

00:09:01.859 --> 00:09:04.400
But that was the compromise that
he was able to come up with.

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:06.170
That was the direction
that he gave.

00:09:06.170 --> 00:09:08.940
And so there was
a sweeping change.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:11.960
There is only one other instance
of a sweeping change like this.

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:15.860
And that happened 1974,
where the name Jap

00:09:15.860 --> 00:09:21.740
was replaced at a system
level with the name Japanese.

00:09:21.740 --> 00:09:24.477
So of all of the
derogatory names

00:09:24.477 --> 00:09:26.060
you can come up with
in your mind that

00:09:26.060 --> 00:09:31.880
would disparage someone's race,
ethnicity, cultural background,

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:34.130
there's only two
that this committee

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:36.150
view as being derogatory.

00:09:36.150 --> 00:09:38.810
There's only those two
words that they will refuse

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:40.990
to approve in a name change.

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:43.910
What I'd say is most frustrating
about this whole process is

00:09:43.910 --> 00:09:47.372
that the committee recognizes
that those two words are so

00:09:47.372 --> 00:09:49.580
bad, they're not going to
approve any new names using

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:51.080
those words.

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:54.320
But there is no process in
place to go back and change

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:55.340
all of the other--

00:09:55.340 --> 00:09:58.160
over 1,000 racist place names
that we have in the country.

00:09:58.160 --> 00:09:59.810
BRANDI: And you
said the last time

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:02.120
there was a sweeping
change was in the '70s?

00:10:02.120 --> 00:10:03.430
MAURICE TURNER: 1974.

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:05.291
BRANDI: Wow.

00:10:05.291 --> 00:10:05.790
Wow.

00:10:05.790 --> 00:10:09.120
So maybe this answer is
obvious, but why did you

00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:13.110
take on this mission beyond
just changing the place

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:15.774
name that you discovered?

00:10:15.774 --> 00:10:17.820
MAURICE TURNER:
As I said earlier,

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:19.810
it literally sat in my stomach.

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:23.430
And it's been sitting there and
bothering me and motivating me

00:10:23.430 --> 00:10:25.890
for almost two years
now, that this is just

00:10:25.890 --> 00:10:28.660
something that needs to change.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:31.870
As we've talked about, we've
known each other for 20 years.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:34.020
And the reason that
we know each other

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:37.080
is very memorable in that
we would go on these field

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:39.910
studies, these field trips
through our high school biology

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:40.410
class.

00:10:40.410 --> 00:10:42.840
And it was such a strong,
positive experience

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:45.870
to go out in nature, meet new
people who then become friends,

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:49.620
experience all the variety
that we have in our country

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:51.090
in a natural way.

00:10:51.090 --> 00:10:54.960
And I think, what
would have changed

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:59.190
in my life experience had we
been out in Yosemite National

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:01.725
Park and I'd come
across a Negro Run?

00:11:01.725 --> 00:11:03.600
How would I have been
able to cope with that?

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:06.300
How would my
teachers, my friends,

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:09.420
my family been able to
explain to me at a young age

00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:11.385
why that name exists
and why it exists

00:11:11.385 --> 00:11:16.617
in such an official capacity?

00:11:16.617 --> 00:11:19.200
BRANDI: I'm guessing there's a
lot of people who are inspired.

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:21.366
They're going to want to
help you with this mission.

00:11:21.366 --> 00:11:25.210
And I know that Dan and
Caleb, who are joining us,

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:27.900
were on the receiving end
of a lot of documentation

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:31.680
from you and of your story.

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.080
I was hoping that
Dan and Caleb, you

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:36.480
can help us understand
the documentation

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:38.970
that Maurice provided
for you guys to help

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:42.252
you make this change on Maps.

00:11:42.252 --> 00:11:44.640
CALEB DAVIS: Sure.

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:50.110
Most of it really boils down to
the offices reports from GNIS.

00:11:50.110 --> 00:11:54.330
And those reports are
really what we need in order

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:56.560
to make changes on the map.

00:11:56.560 --> 00:12:01.020
We need official government
resources, in most cases,

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:03.360
in order to make changes.

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:09.150
So luckily, Maurice had
done all of this legwork.

00:12:09.150 --> 00:12:12.000
We went through an amazing
amount of effort, not only

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.265
to change the name, but he
had also tracked down all

00:12:14.265 --> 00:12:16.500
of this information.

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:18.250
He forwarded it to Dan.

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:21.915
Dan forwarded it to the
[INAUDIBLE] data escalations

00:12:21.915 --> 00:12:24.790
