find a little piece of it,

00:23:48.600 --> 00:23:52.110
wherever they happen to be,
and take that on as a challenge

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:53.200
to get rid of it.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:56.550
So for me, it was Negro
Run in Shenandoah National

00:23:56.550 --> 00:24:00.050
Park in Virginia.

00:24:00.050 --> 00:24:04.740
And I think that if I can go
out and get one little creek

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:08.230
or river renamed, that
anyone else can go do it.

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:10.740
And the cumulative
effect of that is you

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:14.130
would then have
over 1,400 pieces

00:24:14.130 --> 00:24:18.240
of institutionalized
racism gone.

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:20.781
The challenge-- and I'm sure
that folks in the GO team

00:24:20.781 --> 00:24:22.530
understand-- is that
there is this balance

00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:27.149
between factual accuracy
and historical records.

00:24:27.149 --> 00:24:29.190
So I think it's important
to recognize that there

00:24:29.190 --> 00:24:31.300
is history behind these names.

00:24:31.300 --> 00:24:33.930
Places change names over
the course of history.

00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.360
And it's not
necessary that a place

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:38.029
keep its name the entire time.

00:24:38.029 --> 00:24:39.570
But there needs to
be a record of it.

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:41.580
And I think, at least
when we're talking

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:44.190
about place names recognized
by the federal government,

00:24:44.190 --> 00:24:45.900
there's good
recordkeeping, so I'm not

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:48.030
afraid to go out
and ask for a place

00:24:48.030 --> 00:24:51.690
to have a new name that's more
reflective of the community

00:24:51.690 --> 00:24:54.060
that exists today.

00:24:54.060 --> 00:24:55.460
So that's my contribution to it.

00:24:55.460 --> 00:25:00.530
I can't take on all of it
and fix racism in America.

00:25:00.530 --> 00:25:04.800
But I took on a
